<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n11126b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n11" href="#n11126b">N11 (VI.B.5)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n11all.htm#n11126b"> 126(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">H</font> slavetrader</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>Notice</b> Il &eacute;tait le dixi&egrave;me enfant de Ren&eacute;-Auguste, un maitre-homme, qui s&apos;&eacute;tait mis en t&ecirc;te, &agrave; treize ans, de relever son nom avec sa fortune, et qui y parvint: si d&apos;ailleurs il put en 1761 racheter au Mar&eacute;chal de Duras Combourg, le vieux manoir ancestral, ce fut pour avoir arm&eacute; non de pacifique galions, comme le laissent entendre les <i>M&eacute;moires</i> de son fils, mais des corsaires et peut-&ecirc;tre des n&eacute;griers: on a beaucoup remarqu&eacute; que les navires du comte se promenaient beaucoup entre la Guin&eacute;e et les Iles, c&apos;est-&agrave;-dire les Antilles. Aussi bien la traite n&apos;&eacute;tait-elle pas interdite et la pratiquait-on sans d&eacute;roger. <br><font color="green">[Notice: He was the tenth child of Ren&eacute;-August, a capable man, who took it into his head, at the age of thirteen, to restore his name and fortune, and who succeeded in doing so. If moreover he could buy back Combourg, the old ancestral manor, in 1761 from the Marshal of Duras, it was not for having owned peaceful galleons, as his son&apos;s <i>M&eacute;moires</i> imply, but corsairs if not <mark>slave-ships</mark>: it was noticed that the count&apos;s ships often knocked about the sea between Guinea and the Isles, in the West Indies. The slave trade indeed was not prohibited and it was practised without loosing caste.]</font> <small> Chateaubriand, <a name="CHBD" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CHBD"><cite title="source">&OElig;uvres choisies illustr&eacute;es</cite></a> (1912) I, 5-6</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
